00:25:23,772 --> 00:25:27,526
You got some interesting ideas
about law enforcement.

232
00:25:27,693 --> 00:25:33,782
Shoulda stopped the fight. I would have,
but I dearly love seeing Red get stomped.

233
00:25:33,949 --> 00:25:37,912
- He's your deputy?
- He's my sister's boy.

234
00:25:38,078 --> 00:25:42,082
He's so damn mean,
he can't get along with anybody.

235
00:25:42,249 --> 00:25:47,922
He's a real turkey. You move his plate
five inches, he's gonna starve to death.

236
00:25:55,137 --> 00:25:57,890
He's all right. He does that all the time.

237
00:26:09,068 --> 00:26:12,613
This is Gale, this is Shirley.
You met Red.

238
00:26:12,780 --> 00:26:15,366
Now, where you from, son?

239
00:26:16,492 --> 00:26:17,868
Jesus.

240
00:26:20,746 --> 00:26:24,166
Your friend Austin Tucker's long gone.

241
00:26:25,626 --> 00:26:30,047
Did he think that Bridges' drowning
wasn't an accident?

242
00:26:30,214 --> 00:26:35,219
- I don't know. What do you think?
- That's the river, that's the dam.

243
00:26:35,386 --> 00:26:39,265
Open that dam and that water
comes down like a wall.

244
00:26:39,431 --> 00:26:45,271
If you're standing where Bridges was,
you're gonna drown.

245
00:26:45,437 --> 00:26:50,651
Isn't there a warning system or does
the power company love a surprise?

246
00:26:51,568 --> 00:26:57,825
They got sirens and bells and signs all
over the place and they got a watchman.

247
00:26:59,243 --> 00:27:03,038
- There might be just something there.
- Where?

248
00:27:03,205 --> 00:27:06,083
The watchman. Buster Hinton.

249
00:27:06,250 --> 00:27:11,547
Nah! Hell, I've known Buster
for a long time.

250
00:27:11,714 --> 00:27:13,757
I got no reason to doubt him.

251
00:27:14,800 --> 00:27:16,677
No, go ahead.

252
00:27:17,803 --> 00:27:21,390
This might not have
anything to do with anything,

253
00:27:21,557 --> 00:27:25,227
but old Buster showed up
with a brand new shotgun.

254
00:27:25,394 --> 00:27:30,107
- Maybe we ought to talk to him.
- I'd like to do it kinda casual.

255
00:27:30,274 --> 00:27:35,237
He's up at the dam in the afternoons.
I'll take you to where it happened.

256
00:27:35,404 --> 00:27:37,448
You could do some fishing.

257
00:27:37,614 --> 00:27:42,077
- Come up with anything?
- Nothing but fish. You?

258
00:27:42,244 --> 00:27:47,708
I've found out a couple of things, but...
Here, I've brought you some lunch.

259
00:27:48,751 --> 00:27:51,128
You are aces with me.

260
00:27:52,212 --> 00:27:55,591
Look at this! What did you find out?

261
00:28:04,850 --> 00:28:08,395
- That's the warning, huh?
- Yeah, that's it.

262
00:28:08,562 --> 00:28:10,397
Bridges couldn't hear that?

263
00:28:10,564 --> 00:28:13,650
My mother could've heard it
and she's dead.

264
00:28:26,705 --> 00:28:30,000
LD, what's the news
on your friend Buster?

265
00:28:32,920 --> 00:28:34,713
Actually, there is no Buster.

266
00:32:49,676 --> 00:32:53,346
Yeah? Gale! You want LD?

267
00:32:55,015 --> 00:32:58,518
Drowned in what?
The car's right out front.

268
00:33:13,450 --> 00:33:16,119
You gotta be kidding.

269
00:33:17,829 --> 00:33:20,373
Who found the body?

270
00:33:52,322 --> 00:33:56,951
<i>Charley, somebody's broken into
LD's house and stole his car. </i>

271
00:34:04,459 --> 00:34:07,128
<i>Get to the intersection and cut him off. </i>

272
00:34:07,295 --> 00:34:09,839
<i>OK, Red, we're on our way. </i>

273
00:34:26,898 --> 00:34:29,359
<i>We got him cut off. </i>

274
00:35:22,161 --> 00:35:25,623
You've been drinking again, haven't you?

275
00:35:25,790 --> 00:35:28,001
Tell the truth, Joe.

276
00:35:28,167 --> 00:35:30,545
Come in, Stanley.

277
00:35:30,712 --> 00:35:35,758
The thought of covering that council
meeting was too much for you, wasn't it?

278
00:35:35,925 --> 00:35:38,052
Close the door.

279
00:35:44,767 --> 00:35:49,981
Somebody's systematically knocking off
witnesses and you don't care.

280
00:35:50,148 --> 00:35:55,153
Sure I care. I care about my kids' future,
this newspaper, my golf handicap.

281
00:35:55,320 --> 00:35:59,449
I've even been known to care about you,
you ungrateful bastard.

282
00:35:59,616 --> 00:36:05,663
Drink your coffee.
Here. Take it! Shit.

283
00:36:05,830 --> 00:36:09,208
Joe, what evidence have we got?

284
00:36:09,375 --> 00:36:14,172
A girl who died of pills and booze,
a sheriff you say tried to kill you

285
00:36:14,339 --> 00:36:20,470
- And the poor bastard drowns.
- I got a bank book with $107,000 in it.

286
00:36:20,636 --> 00:36:25,016
- The police are after me.
- Why is there no APB on you?

287
00:36:25,183 --> 00:36:28,144
I checked. They say it was an accident.

288
00:36:28,311 --> 00:36:32,607
- They don't wanna answer questions.
- You're damn right.

289
00:36:37,028 --> 00:36:41,449
Sheriff LD Wicker and two deputies
were indicted three months ago

290
00:36:41,657 --> 00:36:46,412
on a utilities scandal.
It was in every paper in the North-West.

291
00:36:46,579 --> 00:36:48,581
He knew you were a reporter,

292
00:36:48,748 --> 00:36:54,295
but it wasn't any national conspiracy
he was covering up.

293
00:36:55,421 --> 00:37:01,302
Remember catching the state senator's
bagman and it was his nephew's bookie?

294
00:37:01,469 --> 00:37:04,847
You're gonna make
a real horse's ass of yourself.

295
00:37:05,014 --> 00:37:10,019
He didn't know I was a reporter. I didn't
tell him, I didn't give him my name.

296
00:37:10,186 --> 00:37:14,816
- Did you register at a hotel?
- Yeah, under a phoney name.

297
00:37:14,982 --> 00:37:20,696
Boy, you amaze me. You go expecting
these things to happen and they do.

298
00:37:22,198 --> 00:37:25,451
Just advance me two weeks' salary.

299
00:37:27,620 --> 00:37:30,456
- For what?
- I gotta find Austin Tucker.

300
00:37:30,623 --> 00:37:33,459
If anybody knows about this, he does.

301
00:37:36,129 --> 00:37:39,382
I won't advance you a dime.

302
00:37:42,885 --> 00:37:47,890
I don't care if your self-serving ambition
gets you the Pulitzer prize.

303
00:37:48,057 --> 00:37:51,269
I'm not gonna have
anything more to do with it.

304
00:37:55,940 --> 00:37:59,902
- Joe...
- Can't help it.

305
00:38:00,611 --> 00:38:02,154
I know.

306
00:38:04,323 --> 00:38:08,369
Good shot. Good shot. You got a point.

307
00:38:10,246 --> 00:38:12,331
Not bad, Riggsy.

308
00:38:13,040 --> 00:38:18,880
- That's good. Hey, babe, you're all right.
- Winning, huh?

309
00:38:19,380 --> 00:38:22,633
Winning? I'm beating the shit out of him.

310
00:38:23,843 --> 00:38:26,470
I'm Schwartzkopf, this is Riggs.

311
00:38:27,597 --> 00:38:32,643
Harry Nelson. The Psych department
gave those vocational tests to you?

312
00:38:34,186 --> 00:38:36,731
I'll go and get those tests.

313
00:38:40,443 --> 00:38:46,699
We establish a centre for the study of
violence, they send us every nut in town.

314
00:38:46,866 --> 00:38:49,994
- They get mean?
- Yeah. Vicious.

315
00:38:50,161 --> 00:38:53,331
One of them bit the ear
off a colleague of mine.

316
00:38:53,497 --> 00:38:57,960
It was OK, though,
we sewed it back on. Most of it.

317
00:38:58,127 --> 00:38:59,587
I'm glad about that.

318
00:39:03,257 --> 00:39:07,094
I'm not sure whoever made this
knew what they were after.

319
00:39:12,183 --> 00:39:16,437
How you doing, Ernie?
It seems to be directing at...

320
00:39:16,604 --> 00:39:22,818
...trying to pull out anger, repression,
frustration, stuff like that.

321
00:39:22,985 --> 00:39:26,947
Could it pick up
potentially homicidal characteristics?

322
00:39:27,114 --> 00:39:30,618
You mean a killer? Yeah, sure.

323
00:39:32,453 --> 00:39:34,747
Would you be willing to go through it

324
00:39:34,914 --> 00:39:40,378
and tell me what answers would come
from a highly violent personality?

325
00:39:40,878 --> 00:39:43,839
Yeah, but it probably
wouldn't do much good.

326
00:39:44,006 --> 00:39:50,096
This stuff's pretty sophisticated.
It's a lot different than my stuff.

327
00:39:50,262 --> 00:39:55,226
It's not any better,
but it would be a difficult...

328
00:40:06,654 --> 00:40:12,743
Fuck it. We'll let Ernie take it.
He'll blow 'em right off the graph.

329
00:40:12,910 --> 00:40:17,039
He hacked up his great-aunt
and killed two ticket-takers.

330
00:40:22,253 --> 00:40:24,338
Ernie?

331
00:40:26,298 --> 00:40:28,426
Come here, boy.

332
00:40:32,138 --> 00:40:36,142
I'd like you to meet somebody.
What's your name again?

333
00:40:36,934 --> 00:40:39,019
Nelson. Harry Nelson.

334
00:40:39,186 --> 00:40:42,481
Harry Nelson, Ernie.

335
00:41:01,876 --> 00:41:04,753
Joe Frady? Looking for Austin Tucker?

336
00:41:08,465 --> 00:41:10,551
D'you wanna see him?

337
00:41:13,179 --> 00:41:15,514
Leave your car here.

338
00:41:19,643 --> 00:41:23,772
- I have to do a skin search.
- A what?

339
00:41:23,939 --> 00:41:27,234
You're gonna strip
and I'm gonna search you.

340
00:41:27,401 --> 00:41:33,282
- Are you out of your fucking mind?
- That's the way Mr Tucker wants it.

341
00:41:33,449 --> 00:41:38,954
And if I don't see you,
you don't see him. All right?

342
00:42:33,258 --> 00:42:38,430
All right, Mr Frady,
who sent you to look for me?

343
00:42:38,597 --> 00:42:41,975
- Nobody sent me.
- Now, look...

344
00:42:42,142 --> 00:42:47,022
I've come 1,300 miles to get
a straight answer to that question.

345
00:42:47,189 --> 00:42:52,444
- My life is in danger just being here.
- Who really sent you?

346
00:42:52,611 --> 00:42:56,281
- Nobody sent me.
- Keep your voice down.

347
00:42:57,658 --> 00:43:00,703
Nobody sent me. I'm a writer...

348
00:43:00,869 --> 00:43:04,289
<i>Stop acting like
you're on The New York Times.</i>

349
00:43:04,456 --> 00:43:10,212
You're a third-rate journalist from Oregon
or wherever the hell you're from.

350
00:43:10,379 --> 00:43:14,216
You've been asking about things
you know nothing about.

351
00:43:14,758 --> 00:43:17,386
There were two attempts
made on my life.

352
00:43:18,053 --> 00:43:20,889
I don't know what you want,
but if it's money...

353
00:43:21,056 --> 00:43:24,059
...l'll give you
$10,000 to keep me out of it.

354
00:43:24,226 --> 00:43:27,813
You don't mention my name
or come looking for me.

355
00:43:27,980 --> 00:43:30,190
All I want is to stay out of it.

356
00:43:30,357 --> 00:43:36,196
Money means nothing to me. This story's
gonna mean more to me than $10,000.

357
00:43:37,156 --> 00:43:40,159
Fella, you don't know
what this story means.

358
00:43:43,245 --> 00:43:45,038
We better talk.

359
00:44:28,749 --> 00:44:31,335
Have you seen this photograph?

360
00:44:34,755 --> 00:44:38,258
It was taken
on the Space Needle that day.

361
00:44:41,011 --> 00:44:45,390
There's me, Lee, Bridges...

362
00:44:49,978 --> 00:44:52,147
You know that man?

363
00:44:52,314 --> 00:44:55,943
- The waiter?
- Yeah. You know his name?

364
00:44:56,109 --> 00:44:58,278
- No, why?
- Just curious.

365
00:45:02,950 --> 00:45:09,748
Lee, Bridges, Joy Holder. Lutz.

366
00:45:11,875 --> 00:45:14,711
Herbie.

367
00:45:29,893 --> 00:45:32,604
Who would have thought?

368
00:47:45,820 --> 00:47:48,531
Sorry, Bill, I didn't mean to scare you.

369
00:47:48,698 --> 00:47:55,121
You're supposed to be dead.
Goddammit. You could have called me.

370
00:47:55,288 --> 00:47:59,334
I was scared shitless
they'd think I was still alive.

371
00:48:00,710 --> 00:48:04,839
- You mean nobody knows?
- Nobody but you.

372
00:48:12,138 --> 00:48:15,934
- Hey, Bill, what's that?
- Tomorrow's lead.

373
00:48:16,101 --> 00:48:20,355
I'm demanding a reopening
of the Carroll investigation.

374
00:48:22,607 --> 00:48:27,445
- Who are you calling?
- The police, FBI, CIA, somebody.

375
00:48:27,612 --> 00:48:30,782
Bill... don't do it.

376
00:48:36,413 --> 00:48:41,626
You suggesting they're involved?
Or that they covered up?

377
00:48:41,793 --> 00:48:45,630
There is a bureaucratic tendency
to cover up mistakes,

378
00:48:45,797 --> 00:48:50,385
but I got no reason to think
any governmental agency was in on it.

379
00:48:50,552 --> 00:48:53,221
Or if they were, that they knew it.

380
00:48:53,388 --> 00:48:57,350
You don't have to infiltrate
the whole agency.

381
00:48:57,517 --> 00:49:01,813
It's not only to do with
the Carroll assassination.

382
00:49:01,980 --> 00:49:07,569
Whoever's behind this
is in the business of recruiting assassins.

383
00:49:07,736 --> 00:49:10,113
Recruiting assassins?

384
00:49:10,280 --> 00:49:15,910
I think I got some of their entrance
exams. If I'm right, I'm gonna enlist.

385
00:49:16,077 --> 00:49:19,164
If you print anything now, I'll be exposed.

386
00:49:19,330 --> 00:49:23,001
You alone can uncover
what all the agencies couldn't?

387
00:49:23,168 --> 00:49:30,133
Maybe. I'm just asking you not to print
anything until I get more evidence.

388
00:49:30,300 --> 00:49:33,887
You'll blow my chance
to find out who's behind it.

389
00:49:34,971 --> 00:49:39,851
- What do you expect me to print?
- My obituary.

390
00:49:40,018 --> 00:49:43,521
I wanna pre-date a will,
name you as executor.

391
00:49:43,688 --> 00:49:47,442
Pick up my things,
give them to the Salvation Army.

392
00:49:47,609 --> 00:49:49,944
Make a big show out of it.

393
00:49:50,111 --> 00:49:53,698
I'm dead and I wanna
stay that way for a while.

394
00:50:04,501 --> 00:50:07,629
It's about $340. It's all I've got here.

395
00:50:08,671 --> 00:50:10,924
You're gonna need the money.

396
00:50:12,258 --> 00:50:15,887
Hope you know
how to take care of yourself.

397
00:50:17,430 --> 00:50:23,228
I hope you do. You're gonna be the only
person who knows what I'm doing.

398
00:50:38,201 --> 00:50:43,164
<i>- Who is it?
- Richard Paley? </i>

399
00:50:43,331 --> 00:50:45,917
<i>- Who is it?
- Are you Richard Paley? </i>

400
00:50:46,084 --> 00:50:47,460
Who?

401
00:50:52,340 --> 00:50:54,300
Who wants him?

402
00:50:55,343 --> 00:50:59,514
Congratulations.
You had some very interesting scores

403
00:50:59,681 --> 00:51:02,642
on the first series of tests for Parallax.

404
00:51:02,809 --> 00:51:06,312
- Testing for what?
- The Parallax Corporation.

405
00:51:06,479 --> 00:51:10,149
You did apply for our training, didn't you?

406
00:51:10,316 --> 00:51:12,777
Oh, Christ, that.

407
00:51:15,446 --> 00:51:21,077
As you know, Parallax receives demands
from all phases of industry.

408
00:51:21,244 --> 00:51:24,831
Demands for unusual personnel.

409
00:51:25,456 --> 00:51:28,334
If you qualify, and we think that you can,

410
00:51:28,501 --> 00:51:33,089
we're prepared to offer you
the most lucrative and rewarding work.

411
00:51:33,256 --> 00:51:38,803
- What do you get out of it?
- We receive a sort of finder's fee.

412
00:51:38,970 --> 00:51:41,931
As I said, the jobs are difficult to fill.

413
00:51:43,474 --> 00:51:46,894
- How tall are you?
- Six-two.

414
00:51:47,937 --> 00:51:54,068
- What kind of jobs you talking about?
- Whatever you're cooking is burning.

415
00:52:06,372 --> 00:52:08,916
You might as well come in.

416
00:52:19,927 --> 00:52:22,221
I'm Jack. Jack Younger.

417
00:52:22,430 --> 00:52:28,478
But we like to be on a first-name basis
with potential candidates.

418
00:52:32,064 --> 00:52:34,442
You look taller than six-two.

419
00:52:34,609 --> 00:52:38,529
What does my height
have to do with anything?

420
00:52:45,661 --> 00:52:50,750
Put some ice on it.
It'll stop the sting and the blister.

421
00:52:52,210 --> 00:52:56,923
Your tests suggest
that you have remarkable talents.

422
00:52:57,089 --> 00:53:02,512
- What do you mean by "talents"?
- You have difficulty holding on to a job.

423
00:53:02,678 --> 00:53:08,351
I just don't like to take a lot of shit,
so people say I got antisocial tendencies.

424
00:53:08,518 --> 00:53:10,895
Has it ever crossed your mind

425
00:53:11,062 --> 00:53:16,025
that it's everybody else's problem
that they don't get along with you?

426
00:53:16,192 --> 00:53:20,530
- Why?
- The very quality that gets you in trouble

427
00:53:20,696 --> 00:53:23,115
makes you potentially invaluable.

428
00:53:23,282 --> 00:53:27,411
- What's that?
- Your aggressiveness.

429
00:53:27,995 --> 00:53:31,541
I don't wanna intrude on you
while you're eating.

430
00:53:31,707 --> 00:53:36,462
Get in touch with me personally
if you'd like to go further.

431
00:53:42,218 --> 00:53:44,762
It's been a pleasure, Richard.

432
00:54:10,830 --> 00:54:12,707
<i>Welcome to the testing room</i>

433
00:54:12,873 --> 00:54:17,545
<i>of the Parallax Corporation's
Division of Human Engineering. </i>

434
00:54:18,587 --> 00:54:21,882
<i>You will now please cross to the chair. </i>

435
00:54:25,011 --> 00:54:27,638
<i>And you will sit down. </i>

436
00:54:27,805 --> 00:54:30,349
<i>Make yourself comfortable. </i>

437
00:54:30,516 --> 00:54:37,690
<i>Be sure to place each one of your hands
on the box on either side of the chair, </i>

438
00:54:37,857 --> 00:54:43,904
<i>making sure that each one of your
fingers is on one of the white rectangles. </i>

439
00:54:45,072 --> 00:54:48,117
<i>Just sit back. Nothing is required of you, </i>

440
00:54:48,284 --> 00:54:52,830
<i>except to observe the visual materials
that are presented. </i>

441
00:54:52,997 --> 00:54:59,170
<i>Be sure to keep your fingers
on the box at all times. </i>

442
00:55:01,672 --> 00:55:06,844
<i>All right. We hope you find the test
a pleasant experience. </i>

443
00:59:54,881 --> 00:59:58,260
<i>Will you please proceed to our offices? </i>

444
00:59:58,427 --> 01:00:01,054
<i>Thank you for your cooperation. </i>

445
01:06:08,504 --> 01:06:13,968
Senator, here's an editorial
even you can't figure out.

446
01:06:14,135 --> 01:06:16,346
Your drink, Senator Gillingham.

447
01:06:16,512 --> 01:06:20,266
This comparison between
you and Carroll is nonsense.

448
01:06:20,433 --> 01:06:23,770
Sorry, sir, you'll have to
go back to coach.

449
01:06:26,606 --> 01:06:31,819
Point is, he doesn't like Hammond
any better than he likes you.

450
01:06:58,513 --> 01:07:00,682
Your name, sir?

451
01:07:00,848 --> 01:07:06,813
- Paley. Richard Paley.
- Is that P-A-I-L-E-Y?

452
01:07:06,979 --> 01:07:12,026
- No, it's P-A-L-E-Y.
- Will you be returning with us?

453
01:07:14,821 --> 01:07:17,699
- Is Denver your final destination?
- Yeah.

454
01:07:17,865 --> 01:07:20,535
That'll be $68.64.

455
01:07:29,752 --> 01:07:32,255
$68.64?

456
01:07:37,385 --> 01:07:39,846
Out of $70.

457
01:09:19,320 --> 01:09:22,448
- What would you like to drink?
- Just a Coke.

458
01:09:59,276 --> 01:10:03,948
Excuse me. Ma'am?
Would you like something to drink?

